    "summary": "KEEP \"impels\" -- Chinese originals differ in force",
    "content": "**KEEP \"impels\"**\n\nThe Chinese originals are genuinely different in force. The body text uses 想要 (want to), which is volitional and softer -- the feeling inclines the subject toward action. The footnote uses 推动, which is mechanistic and stronger -- the feeling drives/pushes the subject into action. \"Impels\" correctly captures 推动's connotation of an external or quasi-external force acting on the agent, which is exactly what the author intends in the footnote: he is explaining that the \"motivation\" (推动力) is what *connects* feeling to behavior, and the word 推动 underscores that this is a force that propels, not merely an inclination.\n\nHarmonizing to \"moves\" would flatten a distinction the author deliberately draws. The body text describes the phenomenal experience from the inside (I *want to* act); the footnote analyzes the structural role of the driving force from the outside (it *pushes* me to act). This inside/outside contrast is philosophically meaningful and should be preserved."
  }
